name: Bash Tips for Linux Sysadmins
message: The Bash shell is a fundamental Linux tool for sysadmins; Carla Schroder explains the basics:
caption: https://www.linux.com/learn/bash-tips-linux-sysadm...

data.message: A nice write up.
If the article is about bash, why does the picture feature csh?

Here's a tip: http://shellcheck.net will probably make the single biggest difference to the quality of your scripts.  Use it.  You'll know you're getting competent when you paste a script in and there's no errors - but don't rest on your laurels there either.  You'll know you're getting better when you paste a script in and there's warnings, but you understand why and also why in certain cases the warning can be ignored.

Absolute beginners may also like http://explainshell.com

Find a decent style guideline.  Google's isn't perfect, but it's an ok starting point: https://google.github.io/styleguide/shell.xml, and abide by it as much as possible.  Most style guidelines will stress that whatever you do: be consistent about it.

Things I'm sick of fixing in scripts that others have written, in no particular order: backticks, parsing ls, useless use of cat, useless use of echo, using echo instead of printf, incorrect use of uppercase vars, little to no comments, any needless full pathing of binaries and no attempt at DRY coding.
Schrod...oh, so close.
Shreyas Srinivasan

Architects and landscapers actually know about this--and they incorporate it into their design process.  In projects that cover large spaces, they will intentionally leave out any paved walkways for a period so they can see where people naturally walk.  Then the come back and pave the paths that people walk.  It's the essence of Bauhaus:  form follows function.

In some cases you can put 'as built' in place of design.   Users will often shortcut well designed and built.   They are just ornery and when you have designed in a little flexibility they will take it too extremes.
